    <text>
        <body>
            <p rend="align(right)"><date>March, 30, 1851</date>.</p>
            <p><placeName>Louisville</placeName>, <date>Sunday, <sic>25thof</sic> second Adar,
                    5611</date></p>
            <p>Very honored <addressee>Mr. Leeser</addressee>:</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">On <date>Friday</date> morning I received your worthy prayer<lb/>
                books <sic>andhasten</sic> to notify you of this, I shall try to sell as many
                as<lb/> possible of them between now and <date>Passover</date>, and to collect for
                the “Oc-<lb/>cident” during the middle days of <date>Passover</date>. And then send
                you a check<lb/> for the entire sum because the few dollars that I have at present
                are<lb/> not worth the trouble. I shall then also notify you what success there<lb/>
                is in the matter of advertising your bible as you wished.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">When you send your “Occidents” here, address the<lb/> following new
                subscribers: <persName>M.Godshaw</persName>, <persName>M.Goldberg</persName>,
                    <persName>H.Stern</persName>, <persName>S.Maas</persName>, <persName>Joseph<lb/>
                    Lieber</persName>. The last two I should not like to state outright as being
                certain<lb/> subscribers. They simply want to try it for a few months., and then,
                if<lb/> the newspaper attracts them they will continue to read it. Above all, I<lb/>
                must confess to you, much to my regret, that I have taken a great deal<lb/> of
                trouble to obtain new subscribers, and that the success is comparative-<lb/>ly very
                slight. One element would gladly read it, but is unable to; an-<lb/>other element is
                naïve enough to admit that they are not pious enough<lb/> and not religious enough;
                one man has no time, another must pay for<lb/> three local newspapers, etc. Only a
                small portion realizes that a worthy<lb/> undertaking ought to be supported. Last
                year you sent me several copies<lb/> of which I distributed some to publishers of
                local newspapers, and others<lb/> to private individuals. This week I collected
                these loaned copies and<lb/> now place them at your disposal. It will be better if,
                in the future,<lb/> you send me only one copy, and thus spare yourself the
                trouble.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In my next letter I shall be in position to tell<lb/> you the cost
                of the various advertisements in the newspapers etc.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">When you write to me again please have the kind-<lb/>ness to let me
                know more exactly what you relations are toward your<lb/> former congregation. I
                still have not given up the hope that in spite<lb/> of the intervention of other
                candidates, you will be re-elected. In my<lb/> next letter I shall, if possible,
                permit myself to send something <del>?</del><lb/> which may be accepted in the
                Occident, for I do not know but that in<lb/> the course of time it may be desirable
                for me to become generally bet-<lb/>ter known than I am at present.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">My wife sends you her best greetings. Accept the<lb/> assurance of
                my esteem, with which I have the honor to sign,</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Your most devoted servant,</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)"><persName role="author">B.H.Gotthelf</persName>.</p>
        </body>
